ants":[{"name":"Faver","meanings":["Altered form of French   Favre   ‘blacksmith’ or of its cognate <b>Lefèvre</b> (see   Lefevre  ). Compare   Favor  .","English: probably in most cases an altered form of   Feaver  , partly because between the 16th and the 18th centuries its pronunciation was sometimes identical with the word favour (see 4 below).","English: occasionally perhaps also a nickname from Middle English (Old French) <i>favo(u)r</i>, Middle English <i>faver</i> ‘help, beauty, grace, benevolence’."]},{"name":"Lefevre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Andre, Emile, Jacques, Joffre, Luc, Adrien, Antoine, Armand, Camille, Eunide, Francois, Germaine.","French and Walloon (<b>Lefèvre</b>): occupational name for a blacksmith or ironworker, Old French <i>fevre</i>, with fused masculine definite article <i>le</i>. One of the most common surnames in France from an early date, coined before the French word for smith, <i>fèvre</i> (from Latin <i>faber</i> ‘maker’), was replaced by <i>forgeron</i>. This surname was also brought to England (in the 16th century by Protestant Walloons and later reinforced by Huguenots from France). It is also established in the Flemish part of Belgium and in Haiti. See also   Lefebvre  , compare   Faver  ,   Lafaver  ,   Lafever  ,   Lefever  , and   Leffew  .","History: This surname is listed (in the form <i>Le Fèvre</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America (in the form <i>Le Fevre</i>)."]},{"name":"Favret","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jacques, Andre, Chantel, Raoul.","French: diminutive of   Favre   ‘blacksmith’."]},{"name":"Farve","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Cecile.","Altered form of French   Favre   ‘blacksmith’."]}]},{"name":"Gérard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gérard DE GAVRE was born about 1310. He married Marie DE SHOENWOUSTRE before 1340, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1312":"1312","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","before 1340":"enne 1340","1340":"1340","about 1310":"umbes 1310","Europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"about 1310–":"noin 1310–Kuollut","1312–Female":"1312–Kuollut","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1312":"1312","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","before 1340":"ennen vuotta 1340","1340":"1340","about 1310":"noin 1310","Europe":"Europe"},"fr":{"about 1310–":"environ 1310–Décédé","1312–Female":"1312–Décédée","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1310–Male":"1310–Décédé","1312":"1312","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","before 1340":"avant 1340","1340":"1340","about 1310":"environ 1310","Europe":"Europe","lifeSummary":"Gérard DE GAVRE est né environ 1310. Il a épousé Marie DE SHOENWOUSTRE avant 1340, à Europe. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"about 1310–":"um 1310–Verstorben","1312–Female":"1312–Verstorben","1340–1388":"1340–1388","1310–Male":"1310–Verstorben","1312":"1312","1388":"1388","1310":"1310","before 1340":"vor 1340","1340":"1340","about 1310":"um 1310","Europe":"Europa","